Based on the overly fancy descriptions Bob used, he ate a **pizza** (specifically, a cheese and tomato pizza on a whole wheat crust). 

Here is the translation of his description:
*   **"Aged organic milk"** = Cheese (which is made by coagulating milk and aging it)
*   **"Seasoned tomato purée"** = Pizza sauce
*   **"Baked whole wheat"** = Whole wheat pizza crust

**What happened?**
Alice was impressed by Bob's pretentious, gourmet-sounding description of his meal, expecting a picture of an elegant, artisanal health food. When she saw the photo, she realized he was just eating a regular pizza, hence her disappointed "wtf" reaction. Bob was using highbrow language to make fast food sound like haute cuisine.

**Was it healthy?**
It's relatively healthier than a standard pizza, but still just pizza. 
The "whole wheat" crust provides more fiber than regular dough, and "organic" and "aged" cheese implies higher quality ingredients with no artificial hormones. Tomato sauce also contains the antioxidant lycopene. However, at the end of the day, it's still a heavy, calorie-dense, high-sodium, high-fat piece of pizza. It's not a "health food" in the way Alice was imagining (like a salad or grilled fish), which is why she was so caught off guard by the photo. [end of text]


